    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>China's Threat to Labor</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Peggy B Musgrave letter on Sept 20 article on China trade bill says flood of United States investment in China could hurt US productivity</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is a pity that the discussion over legislation on trade with China (front page, Sept. 20) does not distinguish between the liberalization of our trade with China and China's easing of restrictions on our investment there. The two have very different consequences.</p>
        <p>Increasing trade is all to the good and allows both countries to specialize in what they do best. Increasing the outflow of American capital, however, can lower productivity here and cost workers their jobs. This explains the opposition to the bill by labor unions.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is a pity that the discussion over legislation on trade with China (front page, Sept. 20) does not distinguish between the liberalization of our trade with China and China's easing of restrictions on our investment there. The two have very different consequences.</p>
        <p>Increasing trade is all to the good and allows both countries to specialize in what they do best. Increasing the outflow of American capital, however, can lower productivity here and cost workers their jobs. This explains the opposition to the bill by labor unions.</p>
        <p>Increased investment abroad is also responsible for the mixed results of the North American Free Trade Agreement alluded to in your article. Opening up China to a flood of American investment is a daunting thought.</p>
        <p>PEGGY B. MUSGRAVE  Santa Cruz, Calif., Sept. 20, 2000</p>
      </block>
